th a red neck and stands near a small red amplifier on the floor. A curly cable runs from the amplifier toward the microphone area. He bends, leans, and steps around energetically while playing, his shaggy hair flying across his face and shoulders.\n\nThe reclining bird passenger reappears, still calm and composed, headphones on and control box in hand. He points upward with one finger, then lowers his hand toward the buttons on the box, as though changing selections again. A close view shows a different pale, long-nosed cartoon man in a dark jacket, white collar, and red tie against the blue sky. He looks worried or uncertain, with raised brows and a slightly open mouth, matching the visual idea of someone reacting nervously to the passenger’s request.\n\nThe view returns to the bird passenger lying beside the “Western” lettering. He keeps the headphones pressed to his ears, nestled into the white pillow, eyes closed again. The curly cord still runs from the headphones and control box off to the right. The white airplane surface with the bold black “Western” lettering fills more of the image as the passenger slides out of view to the right.\n\nThe ending becomes a mostly white airplane surface with a blue triangular area at the left edge. Large red text appears centered on the white surface reading “Hawaii” above “Mexico,” visually presenting destinations associated with Western Airlines.",
